{{Infobox language |name=Alagwa |states=[[Tanzania]] |region=Dodoma region |ethnicity=[[Alagwa people|Alagwa]] |speakers=30,000 |date=2003 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Afro-Asiatic |fam2=[[Cushitic languages|Cushitic]] |fam3=[[South Cushitic languages|South]] |fam4=West Rift |fam5=NW Rift |iso3=wbj |glotto=alag1248 |glottorefname=Alagwa }}
'''Alagwa''' is a [[Cushitic languages|Cushitic]] language spoken in [[Tanzania]] in the Dodoma region.<ref>Raymond G. Gordon Jr., ed. 2005. ''Ethnologue: Languages of the World''. 15th edition. Dallas: Summer Institute of Linguistics.</ref> Some [[Alagwa people|Alagwa]] have shifted to other languages such as [[Sandawe language|Sandawe]].
== Grammar ==
===Word order=== Alagwa sentences have a generalized order [Subject X Auxiliary Y Verb Z], and elements of the sentence other than the subject appear in the positions labelled X, Y, and Z, depending on their information status in the clause. New material tends to appear in the post-verbal position, Z, while old information appears in the pre-auxiliary position, X.
The following example (Kiessling 2007:138) shows the noun '''yaawáa''' 'dowry' introduced as new information after the verb in the first sentence and repeated as old information before the auxiliary '''ningi''' in the second sentence.
{|class='wikitable' |makimoo-w-ód, ||ning-aa|| xay-ee’|| ningi|| bu’-i-yee’|| yaawáa |- |guy-M-D|| SEQ:S3-ABL|| come:3-PF.PL|| SEQ:S3 ||pay-3-PF.PL|| dowry |- |colspan='8'|'that guy, they [i.e. the lions] came and paid the dowry.' |- |maa|| dende’ee-w-ós|| yaawáa|| ningi|| bu’-i-yee’ |- |so ||folks-N-3SG.POSS|| dowry ||SEQ:O3PL|| pay-3-PF.PL |- |colspan='8'|'His folks paid the dowry.' |}
