{{Infobox recurring event | name = Asia Spelling Cup | logo = <!-- Commented out: [[File:QASC2016_Logo_FA-03.jpg|150px|center]] --> | logo_caption = | image = | imagesize = | caption = | date = | begins = | ends = | prev = | next = | frequency = Annual (late October or November) | location = Asia | years_active = | first = 2013<!--"founded=" also works--> | last = | participants = | attendance = | genre = [[Spelling bee]] | budget = | patron = [http://hotel.qooco.com/ Qooco] | organised = <!--"organized=" also works--> | website = [http://www.asiaspell.com/ www.asiaspell.com] | footnotes = }}
The '''Asia Spelling Cup''' is the largest annual [[spelling bee]] in Southeast Asia, and is organised by Qooco, a mobile language learning solutions provider.<ref name="auto">{{cite web|title=SpellinggBeeee Do You Know How To Spell?|url=http://nowjakarta.co.id/spellinggbeeee-do-you-know-how-to-spell/|website=NowJakarta|accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref> The first Asia Spelling Cup took place in [[Singapore]] in 2013,<ref>{{cite web|title=Asia Spelling Cup final competition held in Singapore|url=http://sea.qooco.com/global/news_detail_6.html|website=Qooco|publisher=Qooco|accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref> the next event took place in Bali, [[Indonesia]] in 2014,<ref name="auto1">{{cite news|title=2nd Annual Asia Spelling Cup|url=http://nowbali.co.id/2nd-annual-asia-spelling-cup/|accessdate=25 August 2016|publisher=Now Bali|date=3 November 2014}}</ref> and the next in [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]] in 2015.<ref name="auto2">{{cite news|title=Malaysian and Indonesian students emerge victorious in the Asia Spelling Cup 2015|url=http://seeds.theborneopost.com/2015/11/11/malaysian-and-indonesian-students-emerge-victorious-in-the-asia-spelling-cup-2015/|accessdate=25 August 2016|publisher=Borneo Post|date=11 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Malaysian and Indonesian Students Emerge Victorious in the Asia Spelling Cup 2015|url=http://www.educationdestinationmalaysia.com/news/malaysian-and-indonesian-students-emerge-victorious-in-the-asia-spelling-cup-2015/|website=Education Destination Malaysia|accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref> The 2016 Asia Spelling Cup took place in Bangkok, Thailand, at the Conrad Hotel on November 12, 2016,<ref>{{cite web|title=Indonesia Students to Take Part in 2016 Asia Spelling Cup|url=http://jakartaglobe.id/multimedia/indonesia-students-take-part-2016-asia-spelling-cup/|website=jakartaglobe.id/|publisher=Jakarta Globe|accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref> and the 2017 event took place in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia on November 12, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Asia Spelling Cup|url=http://asiaspell.com/|website=asiaspell.com/|accessdate=2 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=IBRAHIM|first1=IDA NADIRAH|title=This word whiz is not your average 12-year-old|url=http://www.themalaymailonline.com/malaysia/article/this-word-whiz-is-not-your-average-12-year-old#9jzOpp0sBuGGBjm3.97|accessdate=8 March 2018|publisher=Malay Mail|date=21 November 2017}}</ref><ref name="auto3">{{cite news|title=Thailand And China Make History at the Qooco Asia Spelling Cup|url=http://www.bernama.com/en/general/news.php?id=1410723|accessdate=8 March 2018|agency=Bernama|publisher=Bernama|date=15 November 2017}}</ref>
The Asia Spelling Cup draws on primary and secondary school students in various countries in Asia, including [[Malaysia]], Thailand, [[China]] and Indonesia. The 2013 event included Singaporean students.
==The competition== The Asia Spelling Cup consists of two parts, the Pre-Selection process and the finals
==Pre-selection process== The pre-selection process is done online and via mobile, using testing software developed and provided by Qooco.<ref name=":0">{{cite news|title=Singapore, Malaysia students top first Asian spelling competition|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2013/10/05/singapore-malaysia-students-top-first-asian-spelling-competition/|accessdate=25 August 2016|publisher=The Star|date=5 October 2013}}</ref>
After completing the [[online]] tests, students are ranked by score, with the top students chosen for the finals. Pre-selection rounds regularly exceed 100,000 applicants.<ref>{{cite web|title=Malaysian students won the Asian Spelling Cup in Singapore|url=http://schooladvisor.my/news/malaysian-students-won-the-asian-spelling-cup-in-singapore/|website=School Advisor}}</ref>
==Finals== The finals are usually held in a major city in [[Southeast Asia]], in a [[hotel]] conference room or [[resort]].
The Finals are split into two parts, the first part is the [[Primary school]] level competition, and the second part is the [[Secondary school]] level competition.<ref name="auto"/>
