{{Infobox language |name=Danwar |altname= |image=Danuwar Children.jpg |states= [[Nepal]] |speakers={{sigfig|45,800|2}} |date=2011 census |ref=e18 |familycolor=Indo-European |fam2=[[Indo-Iranian languages|Indo-Iranian]] |fam3=[[Indo-Aryan languages|Indo-Aryan]] |fam4=(unclassified) |fam5=Kuswaric |lc1=dhw |ld1=Dhanwar |lc2=dwz
|glotto=dhan1265 |glottorefname=Dhanwar (Nepal) }}
'''Danwar''' (also rendered ''Danuwar'', ''Denwar'', ''Dhanvar'', ''Dhanwar''), is a language spoken in parts of [[Nepal]] by an [[Indo-Aryans|Indo-Aryan]] ethnic group of fifty thousand. It is close to [[Bote-Darai language|Bote-Darai]] but otherwise unclassified within the [[Indo-Aryan languages]].
A variety called Danwar Rai is distinct and may be a separate language. It is not related to the [[Rai languages]] of the Tibeto-Burman family.
